{# users.acl.j2 — Redis 6+ ACL config rendered by the redis-sentinel #}
{# role when `redis_acl_lockdown: true`. F-1213 audit-2026-05-12. #}
{# #}
{# Pre-F-1213: Redis on R1 ran with the default `requirepass` flow + #}
{# the legacy `default` user retaining `on nopass ~* &* +@all` — so a #}
{# password-less client (or any compromised process on the box) could #}
{# enumerate every key + run admin commands like FLUSHALL or DEBUG. #}
{# #}
{# This file closes the legacy default-user surface and replaces it #}
{# with one narrow per-component user that covers the cache key set #}
{# the application actually uses. Operators with stricter posture #}
{# split the per-component user further (aggregator-only / api-only / #}
{# indexer-only) — each gets its own >password and ~keypattern. #}
{# Today the application binaries share `redis_password` so a single #}
{# `ratesengine` user is sufficient. #}

# Disable the legacy default user. `off` means it cannot AUTH at all
# — every connection MUST authenticate as one of the named users
# below. Combined with `protected-mode yes` in redis.conf this
# eliminates the "compromised local process gets everything" path.
user default off nopass nocommands

# Application user. ONE password shared with every application
# binary today (aggregator + indexer + api + customerwebhook
# worker); future per-component split adds parallel users with
# their own >password lines.
#
# Command surface (`+@read +@write +@scripting +@pubsub` minus the
# admin/dangerous families):
#
#   - @read       — GET / HGET / LRANGE / SMEMBERS / ZRANGE / EXISTS
#   - @write      — SET / DEL / EXPIRE / HSET / SADD / ZADD / INCR
#   - @scripting  — EVAL / EVALSHA (rate-limit token bucket)
#   - @pubsub     — SUBSCRIBE / PUBLISH (closed-bucket stream)
#   - @connection — AUTH / PING / SELECT / HELLO (everyone needs these)
#
# Explicitly DENIED (each `-cmd` overrides the `+@write`-default
# permission):
#
#   - @admin      — CONFIG SET / DEBUG / SHUTDOWN / FLUSHALL / FLUSHDB
#   - @dangerous  — KEYS (full-keyspace scan), MIGRATE, MODULE,
#                   CLUSTER, REPLICAOF, SLAVEOF, FAILOVER, RESET,
#                   FUNCTION, ACL, CLIENT KILL, LATENCY, MEMORY
#                   DOCTOR, OBJECT, SLOWLOG, MONITOR, COMMAND COUNT
#
# Key-pattern allow-list (`~`) restricts the user to the cache key
# prefixes the application actually uses. Anything outside the list
# (operator scratch keys, third-party tool spillover) is invisible.
user ratesengine on >{{ redis_password }} \
  -@all +@read +@write +@scripting +@pubsub +@connection \
  -@admin -@dangerous \
  ~vwap:* ~confidence:* ~freeze:* ~div:* \
  ~rl:* ~signup-ip:* ~signup:email:* ~signup:lock:* ~signup:verify:* ~touch:apikey:* \
  ~toml:* ~meta:* ~price:* ~apikey:* ~health:* ~oracle:* \
  ~sub:* ~sep10:seen:* ~usage:* \
  ~assets:list:* ~markets:list:* \
  &closed-bucket-* &stream-*
# F-1254 (codex audit-2026-05-12): the previous allow-list named
# `~ratelimit:*` (code writes `rl:*`) and `~subscriber:*` (code
# writes `sub:*`), and omitted `~signup:email:*`, `~sep10:seen:*`,
# `~usage:*`, `~assets:list:*`, `~markets:list:*` entirely. A
# lockdown-on deployment would have authenticated successfully and
# then ACL-denied at runtime on rate-limit / signup duplicate /
# SEP-10 replay / usage accounting / catalogue cache writes. The
# canonical list is in `internal/cachekeys/keys.go` plus the per-
# component WithKeyPrefix sites in ratelimit, signup_tracker,
# sep10/redisreplay, and usage/counter. Update this allow-list
# in lockstep when a new namespace lands.
#
# F-1255 (codex audit-2026-05-12): `signup:lock:*` is the SETNX
# per-email serialisation namespace the dashboardauth callback
# acquires before Account.Create to keep concurrent first-login
# callbacks from racing.
#
# F-1226 wave 39 (codex audit-2026-05-12): `touch:apikey:*` is
# the SETNX-debounce namespace the api-key TouchUsage middleware
# uses to gate hot-row UPDATEs on the api_keys table.
#
# F-1218 wave 42 (codex audit-2026-05-12): `signup:verify:*` is
# the email-ownership-proof token namespace. The signup handler
# Reserves a hashed token after minting; the /v1/signup/verify
# endpoint Consumes it via GETDEL. Disjoint from `signup:email:`
# (the F-1218 prior-signup reservation) and `signup:lock:` (the
# F-1255 per-email serialisation lock).

# Exporter user — narrow command set the oliver006/redis_exporter
# binary needs for INFO / CLIENT / CLUSTER / CONFIG GET / DBSIZE /
# SLOWLOG GET metric gathering. Cannot reuse the `ratesengine`
# application user because that user has `-@admin -@dangerous` to
# deny FLUSHALL / DEBUG / etc., and INFO / CLIENT / CLUSTER /
# CONFIG / SLOWLOG all live in those denied categories.
#
# Same `redis_password` so the vault rotation is one-shot across
# every named user; the username is what differentiates the ACL
# roles. The exporter's systemd unit at
# `tasks/07-monitoring.yml` passes `-redis.user=redis_exporter`
# so the exporter sends `AUTH redis_exporter <pass>` instead of
# the legacy single-arg AUTH that would resolve as `default` and
# be rejected under lockdown.
#
# F-1272 (codex audit-2026-05-13): wave-106 adds this user
# specifically because the wave-106 exporter wiring referenced
# `-redis.user=redis_exporter`; without the matching ACL entry
# the exporter would fail under lockdown.
user redis_exporter on >{{ redis_password }} \
  -@all +@connection \
  +info +client +cluster|info +config|get +dbsize +slowlog|get +latency \
  ~* &*

{# When the operator wants per-component lockdown they uncomment #}
{# the three users below (rotating distinct passwords through the #}
{# vault) and stop the API / aggregator / indexer binaries with #}
{# their own narrower `REDIS_PASSWORD` env vars: #}
{# #}
